<subSubSection pageId="13" pageNumber="63" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="13.[151,1436,151,573]" pageId="13" pageNumber="63">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,332,357]" pageId="13" pageNumber="63">Remarks.</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Gressitt, J. L." box="[324,508,332,357]" journalOrPublisher="Lingnan Science Journal" pageId="13" pageNumber="63" pagination="161 - 186" part="18" refString="Gressitt, J. L. (1939 a) Hispine beetles in the collection of the Lingnan natural history survey and museum (Coleoptera: Chrysomelidae: Cassidinae). Lingnan Science Journal, 18, 161 - 186 + pl. 5." title="Hispine beetles in the collection of the Lingnan natural history survey and museum (Coleoptera: Chrysomelidae: Cassidinae)" type="journal article" year="1939" yearSuffix="a">Gressitt (1939a)</bibRefCitation>
provisionally identified the two specimens from Luofu Shan as 
<taxonomicName authority="Baly, 1869" authorityName="Baly" authorityYear="1869" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Downesia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="63" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tarsata">
<emphasis box="[1252,1368,333,356]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="63">D. tarsata</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Baly, J. S." journalOrPublisher="Transactions of the Entomological Society of London" pageId="13" pageNumber="63" pagination="363 - 382" part="1869" publicationUrl="http://dx.doi.org/10.1111/j.1365-2311.1869.tb01112.x" refString="Baly, J. S. (1869) Descriptions of new genera and species of Hispidae; with notes on some previously described species. Transactions of the Entomological Society of London, 1869, 363 - 382. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.1111 / j. 1365 - 2311.1869. tb 01112. x" title="Descriptions of new genera and species of Hispidae; with notes on some previously described species" type="journal article" year="1869">Baly, 1869</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
based on brown body but noted that the two specimens differ in tarsi not being black. Later on, 
<bibRefCitation author="Gressitt, J. L." journalOrPublisher="Lingnan Science Journal" pageId="13" pageNumber="63" pagination="53 - 142" part="23" refString="Gressitt, J. L. (1950) The Hispine beetles of China (Coleoptera: Chrysomelidae). Lingnan Science Journal, 23, 53 - 142 + pls. 4 - 8." title="The Hispine beetles of China (Coleoptera: Chrysomelidae)" type="journal article" year="1950">Gressitt (1950)</bibRefCitation>
decided that they are enough distinct and described them a new species 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Gressitt" authorityYear="1950" box="[1047,1139,404,429]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Downesia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="63" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="balyi">
<emphasis box="[1047,1139,404,429]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="63">D. balyi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and compared the species briefly to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Baly" authorityYear="1869" box="[265,380,441,464]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Downesia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="63" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tarsata">
<emphasis box="[265,380,441,464]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="63">D. tarsata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. However, the 
<typeStatus box="[557,655,439,464]" pageId="13" pageNumber="63">holotype</typeStatus>
is a teneral specimen whose brown colouration is due to a not fully sclerotized body. The natural colouration of the species is probably much darker, most likely very dark brown or nearly black. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Baly" authorityYear="1869" box="[306,507,513,536]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Downesia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="63" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tarsata">
<emphasis box="[306,507,513,536]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="63">Downesia tarsata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is very different as it has the second sutural row of punctures developed only on apical fourth of the elytra while 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Gressitt" authorityYear="1950" box="[511,601,548,573]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Downesia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="63" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="balyi">
<emphasis box="[511,601,548,573]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="63">D. balyi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has it distinct from basal fourth.
</paragraph>
